File: /home/baron/projects/campfire/cmd/cf/cmd/read.go, runNATPoll (line 408-414)

In one-shot (non-follow) mode, the error retry logic is:
  if !cfg.follow {
      if peerIdx == 0 {
          return fmt.Errorf("polling peers: %w", err)
      }
  }

peerIdx is incremented modulo len(peers) BEFORE this check. So after a failure on peer 0, peerIdx becomes 1. The code continues to peer 1. If peer 1 also fails, peerIdx becomes 2 (or wraps to 0 if len=2). If it wraps to 0, the error is returned.

Problem: for a single-peer scenario (len(peers) == 1), peerIdx = (0+1) % 1 = 0. So after the FIRST failure on the only peer, peerIdx == 0 and the error is returned. This is correct.

For a 2-peer scenario where both peers fail: peer 0 fails, peerIdx becomes 1. Then the loop continues (no error returned since peerIdx != 0). Peer 1 fails, peerIdx becomes 0. Error returned. But the last error returned is from peer 1, not peer 0. This loses peer 0s error message. Minor issue.

More seriously: for 3+ peers where ONLY peer 0 fails and the others succeed, the code would return the peer 0 error after wrapping around even though a successful peer existed. Wait, no — on success the break exits the loop. The issue only manifests when ALL peers fail and peerIdx wraps.

Actually a subtle bug: if peer 0 fails then peer 1 succeeds (returns data), the cursor advances and the function breaks. Good. But if peer 0 succeeds with no messages (len(msgs) == 0), the code hits "if !cfg.follow { break }" and exits. This is the intended behavior.

The real bug: if the first poll succeeds but returns 0 messages, the cursor is NOT updated (newCursor is only set when len(msgs) > 0). But on 204 from the server, Poll returns (nil, cursor, nil) — cursor unchanged. So the next call would re-poll from the same position. This is correct for one-shot mode (no retransmission), but the cursor variable remains at the initial value regardless of server-side 204. This is intentional but worth noting the cursor never advances on empty poll.

## Bug

runViewRead (cmd/cf/cmd/view.go:234) fetches ALL messages with `s.ListMessages(campfireID, 0)` (no filter), then applies the predicate. This means campfire:view definition messages are included in the candidate set.

For most predicates this is harmless (the campfire:view messages don't match `(tag "memory:standing")` etc). But for negation predicates like `(not (tag "foo"))` or `(not (tag "memory:standing"))`, the campfire:view system messages will appear in results, since they don't have those tags.

The test TestViewRead_PredicateFilters manually skips view messages in its own evaluation loop (see the isViewMsg check), but runViewRead itself does NOT skip them.

## Fix
Filter out campfire:view messages before predicate application in runViewRead. Either:
1. Add a post-filter after matching: skip records whose tags include campfire:view
2. Or pre-filter using a negative filter

Simplest fix — after building matched, filter to exclude campfire:view tag:
```go
for _, m := range allMsgs {
    ctx := buildMessageContext(m)
    // Skip system messages (view definitions etc) from results.
    isSystem := false
    for _, tag := range ctx.Tags {
        if strings.HasPrefix(tag, "campfire:") {
            isSystem = true
            break
        }
    }
    if isSystem {
        continue
    }
    if predicate.Eval(pred, ctx) {
        matched = append(matched, m)
    }
}
```

File: cmd/cf/cmd/view.go, function runViewRead, around line 241-246

Done condition: runViewRead never returns campfire:* system messages in its output, verified by a test that uses a negation predicate.

File: /home/baron/projects/campfire/pkg/threshold/threshold.go, RunDKG (line 159-246)

In the goroutine for each participant (line 206-233), the drainDKG function loops calling p.ProcessAll() and routing messages via routeDKG. If routeDKG returns an error (line 178-179, 198-201), the error is logged with continue but the message is dropped. The participant that was supposed to receive this message will never get it and will block forever on its Done() channel.

The WaitGroup wg.Wait() on line 235 will then deadlock because that goroutine never returns.

The channels are buffered (n*n*8) which is generous, but if MarshalBinary fails (extremely unlikely but possible if memory allocation fails), the message is dropped and the corresponding goroutine blocks forever.

Additionally, the drainDKG function does NOT check p.Done() inside the ProcessAll loop:
  func drainDKG(p *DKGParticipant, uid uint32) {
      for {
          select {
          case <-p.Done(): return
          default:
          }
          out := p.ProcessAll()
          if len(out) == 0 { return }
          ...
      }
  }

The Done() check is non-blocking (select with default). If Done() fires and out is non-empty in the same iteration, the function returns early leaving messages unrouted. But Done() closing means the DKG is complete, so subsequent messages would be ignored anyway.

The main risk is the deadlock scenario from dropped messages due to MarshalBinary errors.

In cmd/cf/cmd/send.go, checkRoleCanSend is called TWICE (lines 92 and 108) with the comment "Must run after future and fulfills are appended so the check sees the complete tag set (workspace-w97)":

```go
// First call (pre-mutation) at line 92:
if err := checkRoleCanSend(m.Role, sendTags); err != nil {
    return err
}

// tags gets mutated (future/fulfills appended)
tags := sendTags
if sendFuture { tags = append(tags, "future") }
if sendFulfills != "" { tags = append(tags, "fulfills") }

// Second call (post-mutation) at line 108:
if err := checkRoleCanSend(m.Role, tags); err != nil {
    return err
}
```

The first call is redundant: it checks sendTags before mutation, but since "future" and "fulfills" are user-defined tags (not campfire:* system tags), they cannot cause the first check to fail if the second check will also pass. The first call could only catch observer-role issues that the second call would also catch.

This is a code smell from a defensive fix that left dead code behind. The first call should be removed; only the post-mutation check is needed.

Severity: MEDIUM - dead code obscures the intent; a reviewer cannot easily understand why both checks exist.

File: /home/baron/projects/campfire/pkg/transport/http/handler.go, handleRekey (line 807-1011)

The rekey handler receives a RekeyMessageCBOR field in the request body (line 989-1008). The handler decodes and stores this CBOR message as a rekey event, but it never verifies the signature of the rekeyMsg.

On line 989-1008:
  if len(req.RekeyMessageCBOR) > 0 {
      var rekeyMsg message.Message
      if cfencoding.Unmarshal(req.RekeyMessageCBOR, &rekeyMsg) == nil {
          ...
          h.store.AddMessage(store.MessageRecord{...})
      }
  }

There is no call to rekeyMsg.VerifySignature() before storing. The rekey message is supposed to be signed by the OLD campfire key to prove the eviction was authorized. Without signature verification, any peer (or a compromised peer) could send an arbitrary RekeyMessageCBOR that gets stored as a legitimate rekey event in the target peer's history.

The request itself is signed by the sender's agent key (verified on line 826-830), but the embedded CBOR rekey message has its own signature from the campfire key that is not checked.

Impact: a malicious peer who can post to the /rekey endpoint (with valid agent signatures) can inject arbitrary campfire:rekey messages into another peer's message history, potentially forging eviction events or poisoning the event log.
